The brothers of the Alpha Tau Chapter of Lambda Phi Epsilon at UVA have been working closely in a coalition with other Lambda chapters in the Southeast region called Lambdas For Change. Our goal was to raise money for Campaign Zero, an anti-police brutality organization, and support the Black Lives Matter movement as a whole. 
In total, we have been able to internally raise $5005 dollars, which will be matched by Capital One Bank with the help of our alumni. In addition, we have written a statement of solidarity with the Black community as well as compiled a list of educational resources. 
We urge our community: do not become complacent. We will not be stopping our support here and neither should you. We hope our efforts can help serve as a call to action for others to spread awareness, donate, protest, and make your voices heard. A link to our full statement and further resources can be found in a link in our bio! 
We are extremely grateful for the support from alumni and active brothers all across the Southeast region. This wouldn‚Äôt have been possible without you. Stay safe everyone!

Furthermore, the brothers of the Alpha Tau Chapter of Lambda Phi Epsilon do not condone this behavior nor do we support the messages found in the screenshots that became public today. Racism has no place in our brotherhood. These actions will not be tolerated and steps must be taken in order to stop such commentary. As a chapter, we are committed to taking steps in holding discussions and becoming better educated ourselves as we consider the roots and expressions of anti-Blackness in our community. We should not and cannot be passive bystanders. 
It is important to recognize communities that are hurting and now more than ever we must seek solidarity. Making divisive racist remarks and holding such views is not acceptable and we collectively need to take steps towards education and greater awareness. Minorities should be standing together in these troubling times rather than apart as it is through unity social progress is made. It is imperative to seek out uncomfortable conversations and have discussions about these deep rooted issues as that is the only way we can move forward. 
Echoing the statement made by the entire fraternity: we stand in solidarity with the National APIDA Panhellenic Association against anti-Black racism. Please see the link in our bio for more information.

Next up for a Fourth Year Feature is  former Vice President Financial #93 Roman ‚ÄúS.P.Q.R.‚Äù Wang! 
Major: BA Mathematics, BA Computer Science

Q: What are your plans after college?

A: I'll be moving to Baltimore after graduation to concurrently work for Johns Hopkins Applied Physics Lab and pursue a Masters in Computer Science at Johns Hopkins University. JHU APL invents and engineers a lot of stuff for the government from thought-controlled prosthetic limbs to asteroid deflectors. I'll be presenting at the International Conference on Computer Communications and Networks (ICCCN) this year in Spain and hope to have my work be published in a journal one day. In my free time, I really want to explore art/creating art in all of its forms!

Q: What advice would you give to younger students? 
A: There are things you know, things you don‚Äôt know, things you know you don‚Äôt know. Really prioritize gaining knowledge in the third category, which usually involves pursuit of new experience and activities that can help you understand yourself, further develop what you value, and create a strong mentality that can propel you through the rest of life. Make the most out of that $30k (minus UVA slush fund expenditures) worth of resources provided by the school and this time period as you won‚Äôt be able to relive it again.

We are going to miss you so much bro, don‚Äôt be a stranger and swing by and see us sometime!

üîπüê≤ FOURTH YEAR FEATURE üê≤ üîπ
Our second Fourth Year Feature goes to former president #87 Michael "Forrest Dump" Wu!

Major: B.S. Computer Science

Q: What are your plans after college?
A: After college, I will be moving to Maryland working as a software engineer for Naval Information Warfare Center Atlantic. Long term, I will be looking forward to traveling and possibly in a couple of years coming back to school for a master's degree.

Q: What advice would you give to underclassmen?
A: Honestly college is a unique opportunity that affords you new people to meet, new connections to make, and new experiences to find. Make the most of every opportunity you get, always thank the people you meet, and take risks in discovering new skills. Never stop learning, never become complacent. Above all, do the things you want to do, not because you were told to or out of obligation, but because they will make you happy and it is on your terms. Live the life you want without ever regretting the past.

üîπüê≤ FOURTH YEAR FEATURE üê≤ üîπ
Our very first Fourth Year Feature goes to former house scroll #86 Edmund "Netflixxx and J.I.L.L." Pan!

Major: B.S. Systems Engineering

Q: What are your plans after college?
A: I'm going to Houston as a consultant for a small tech consulting firm called Pariveda Solutions. What drew me to Pariveda was the company's quality of work and training and their focus on work/life balance. I hope to hone by consulting and CS skills while I figure out what I want to do with my life.

Q: What advice would you give to underclassmen?
A: Have fun, kids. College is pretty much the tutorial stage for real life. No one really knows what they're doing. A couple years ago, everyone was living with their mom. If you want to go far, you're going to need some badasses in your party. Make sure they know how to have fun but also that they're dependable and have good values. You're going to be going to these people a lot. If you don't have these people in your life, try to focus on helping others. Not everything is about you, and good things will come your way. If you make mistakes, don't worry about it. You're doing the best you can with what you know; it's all part of the game. Sometimes you need to battle the boss a couple times before you figure him out. Also you should study abroad it's a very fun mini-game I promise. ‚úå
